WEBVTT

00:00.133 --> 00:09.608
♪

00:09.610 --> 00:11.744
Joe:
<i> We never had a choice.</i>

00:11.746 --> 00:14.146
♪♪

00:14.148 --> 00:16.815
<i> We never even realized</i>
<i> we had a choice</i>

00:16.817 --> 00:22.755
<i> About sitting in chairs</i>
<i> until it was too late.</i>

00:22.757 --> 00:25.490
<i> If you are a western person</i>
<i> like me,</i>

00:25.492 --> 00:29.294
<i> Our tendons and muscles</i>
<i> have shortened from disuse</i>

00:29.296 --> 00:31.630
<i> And our natural</i>
<i> resting position,</i>

00:31.632 --> 00:34.633
<i> The squat, is gone forever.</i>

00:34.635 --> 00:40.705
♪♪

00:40.707 --> 00:43.976
<i> I guess instead of feeling bad</i>
<i> about what I've lost,</i>

00:43.978 --> 00:47.512
<i> I should be grateful for what</i>
<i> I was given --</i>

00:47.514 --> 00:50.315
<i> A big, juicy butt.</i>

00:50.317 --> 00:53.051
<i> And consider the choice</i>
<i> I do have --</i>

00:53.053 --> 00:55.654
<i> What kind of chair</i>
<i> I should sit on.</i>

00:55.656 --> 01:03.528
♪♪

01:03.530 --> 01:08.333
<i> In the past year, I've found</i>
<i> I could no longer sit still,</i>

01:08.335 --> 01:12.937
<i> Not in any of the chairs I own</i>
<i> or any others I've tried,</i>

01:12.939 --> 01:15.474
<i> So I figured</i>
<i> I'd try to build my own.</i>

01:15.476 --> 01:23.548
♪♪

01:23.550 --> 01:31.623
♪♪

01:31.625 --> 01:34.493
[ sawing ]

01:34.495 --> 01:39.164
♪♪

01:39.166 --> 01:43.702
♪♪

01:43.704 --> 01:46.839
<i> This is my first attempt</i>
<i> at making a chair</i>

01:46.841 --> 01:49.675
<i> So please</i>
<i> don't watch as guidance.</i>

01:51.045 --> 01:54.179
<i> More like</i>
<i> a live-tv motorcycle jump,</i>

01:54.181 --> 01:56.849
<i> You can watch to see</i>
<i> what goes wrong.</i>

02:22.543 --> 02:26.879
<i> Here's my design</i>
<i> for the chair I'm making.</i>

02:26.881 --> 02:28.280
<i> Just kidding.</i>

02:28.282 --> 02:30.549
<i> A joke for</i>
<i> the woodworkers watching.</i>

02:30.551 --> 02:34.219
<i> They're going to tear me apart</i>
<i> in the comments section anyhow,</i>

02:34.221 --> 02:37.355
<i> So I figured I'd josh them</i>
<i> by suggesting I could make</i>

02:37.357 --> 02:41.560
<i> A sam maloof rocker.</i>

02:41.562 --> 02:42.827
<i> I should really be starting</i>

02:42.829 --> 02:45.297
<i> With a cupholder</i>
<i> or cutting board.</i>

02:45.299 --> 02:50.034
<i> Making a chair on my first go</i>
<i> is shooting for the sun.</i>

02:50.036 --> 02:53.706
<i> But lately I have been trying</i>
<i> a lot more new things,</i>

02:53.708 --> 02:57.842
<i> Like putting together a party</i>
<i> for my girlfriend, sarah,</i>

02:57.844 --> 03:00.178
<i> Which went pretty well.</i>

03:00.180 --> 03:02.046
<i> For the most part.</i>

03:02.048 --> 03:04.449
♪♪

03:04.451 --> 03:06.184
<i> That's maple.</i>

03:06.186 --> 03:08.320
♪♪

03:08.322 --> 03:10.389
Mike: God damn it!

03:10.391 --> 03:12.657
Yes!
Did you see?

03:12.659 --> 03:13.926
I got a strike!

03:13.928 --> 03:15.994
[ laughter ]
♪ I got a strike ♪

03:15.996 --> 03:17.662
That's right!
I got it!
Go, cowgirl!

03:17.664 --> 03:19.131
Oh!
Thank you.

03:19.133 --> 03:20.999
It fits you.
Don't take it off.

03:21.001 --> 03:23.067
Okay. Okay.
Okay?

03:23.069 --> 03:26.138
Wssh, right down.
Okay?

03:26.140 --> 03:27.539
'cause then you get
some force on it.

03:27.541 --> 03:29.608
Hey!
Guys, guys.

03:29.610 --> 03:31.676
Debin: Ahem!
Okay.

03:31.678 --> 03:33.612
Sarah, we just wanted to say

03:33.614 --> 03:36.748
That we didn't even realize we
were looking for another friend,

03:36.750 --> 03:38.751
But you opened up
our minds to it.

03:38.753 --> 03:41.620
[ laughs ]
and a lot of other weird stuff,

03:41.622 --> 03:43.355
Like camping gear.

03:43.357 --> 03:44.689
[ laughter ]

03:44.691 --> 03:46.891
Happy birthday,
sweetie!
Happy birthday!

03:46.893 --> 03:48.493
Salut!
Salut!
Salut!

03:48.495 --> 03:50.495
Salut.
Mike: God damn it!

03:50.497 --> 03:51.496
Aagh!

03:51.498 --> 03:52.965
[ woman laughs ]

03:52.967 --> 03:55.768
Ohh!

03:55.770 --> 03:57.970
Ohh!

03:57.972 --> 04:00.773
Ohh!
Sue: Chill out!

04:00.775 --> 04:02.374
♪ drink beer
from plastic cups ♪

04:02.376 --> 04:04.709
That way, country girl.
That way.
♪ all night ♪

04:04.711 --> 04:07.712
♪ where you goin' tonight? ♪
♪ where you goin' tonight? ♪

04:07.714 --> 04:09.447
♪ where you goin'
tonight? ♪

04:09.449 --> 04:11.650
♪ where you goin'
tonight? ♪

04:11.652 --> 04:12.651
Aah!
[ thud ]

04:12.653 --> 04:14.787
Sarah!
Ugh! Ow!

04:15.589 --> 04:18.991
<i> We ended up spending</i>
<i> most the night at the e.R.</i>

04:18.993 --> 04:21.259
<i> Till they could put</i>
<i> a cast on her wrist.</i>

04:21.261 --> 04:23.996
<i> I told her she is becoming</i>
<i> like the mummy</i>

04:23.998 --> 04:26.799
<i> But she absolutely hated that</i>
<i> and told me to shut up.</i>

04:26.801 --> 04:31.736
<i> Anyhow, she is having a tough</i>
<i> go at it right now</i>

04:31.738 --> 04:34.206
<i> And wanted to be alone today.</i>

04:38.212 --> 04:42.047
<i> Ready for next steps,</i>
<i> but that's enough for now.</i>

04:46.353 --> 04:50.022
<i> New materials have always led</i>
<i> to new types of chairs.</i>

04:50.024 --> 04:52.424
<i> The possibilities</i>
<i> are endless.</i>

04:52.426 --> 04:56.294
<i> But you probably know by now</i>
<i> that a wood chair suits me.</i>

04:56.296 --> 04:59.297
<i> So I went back</i>
<i> to my friend john's property</i>

04:59.299 --> 05:00.899
<i> Where sarah and I camped</i>
<i> last fall</i>

05:00.901 --> 05:03.836
<i> And saw that the deceased ash</i>
<i> was still there</i>

05:03.838 --> 05:05.570
<i> And asked</i>
<i> if I could have it.</i>

05:05.572 --> 05:08.373
<i> I'm not quite sure how I'll get</i>
<i> it out of the woods, but...</i>

05:08.375 --> 05:10.642
John: I guess I don't know
how I would, either.

05:10.644 --> 05:12.377
Y-you go ahead.

05:12.379 --> 05:14.680
Joe: Really?
Yeah.

05:26.326 --> 05:28.727
<i> In the moments when I haven't</i>
<i> been helping</i>

05:28.729 --> 05:30.529
<i> Or worrying about sarah,</i>

05:30.531 --> 05:34.266
<i> I've been thinking about gene's</i>
<i> campaign video.</i>

05:34.268 --> 05:37.670
<i> He and gabriel put together</i>
<i> the world they'd like to see</i>

05:37.672 --> 05:41.373
<i> And I admit,</i>
<i> it sucked me in a little bit.</i>

05:43.477 --> 05:50.549
♪♪

05:50.551 --> 05:57.689
♪♪

05:57.691 --> 06:04.563
♪♪

06:04.565 --> 06:07.499
<i> Clearly a vision</i>
<i> by a retired freighter captain</i>

06:07.501 --> 06:10.502
<i> And a 12-year-old boy raised</i>
<i> among scientists</i>

06:10.504 --> 06:13.037
<i> On a research base</i>
<i> in antarctica,</i>

06:13.039 --> 06:16.008
<i> But also a compelling one.</i>

06:17.111 --> 06:25.183
♪♪

06:25.185 --> 06:33.258
♪♪

06:41.868 --> 06:45.337
<i> I mean, it's very hard to argue</i>
<i> with some of their ideas.</i>

06:45.339 --> 06:54.146
♪♪

06:56.550 --> 06:58.817
Gene:<i> ...Advances,</i>
<i> the machines can produce</i>

06:58.819 --> 07:02.955
<i> Adequate life support</i>
<i> in half the present time.</i>

07:02.957 --> 07:06.891
<i> But in the end,</i>
<i> what it all boils down to is</i>

07:06.893 --> 07:09.294
<i> Public transportation.</i>

07:09.296 --> 07:13.431
♪♪

07:13.433 --> 07:14.833
Wow.

07:14.835 --> 07:16.969
What did you think?

07:16.971 --> 07:18.971
It's great, gene.

07:18.973 --> 07:21.306
I didn't want to get
into politics.

07:21.308 --> 07:23.241
We just thought
it was ridiculous

07:23.243 --> 07:26.511
That no other politicians
were offering a 100-year plan.

07:26.513 --> 07:31.583
I guess one concern is that
president of the world

07:31.585 --> 07:34.853
Sounds like a, uh,
dictatorship.

07:34.855 --> 07:35.988
No, joe, no.

07:35.990 --> 07:38.056
I'll only stay in office

07:38.058 --> 07:39.858
Until we can set up
a supercomputer

07:39.860 --> 07:42.194
To distribute resources
without bias.

07:42.196 --> 07:43.796
But doesn't all tech--

07:43.798 --> 07:46.264
Technology have biases?

07:46.266 --> 07:48.733
It's...

07:48.735 --> 07:50.202
We're working on it.

07:50.204 --> 07:54.072
Okay.
Those are my questions.

07:54.074 --> 07:57.209
Oh, yeah.
How'd you guys meet?

07:57.211 --> 07:59.544
Oh, uh, my parents and me

07:59.546 --> 08:01.880
Went to a furniture store
to buy a sofa.

08:01.882 --> 08:04.683
A low-profile sectional.

08:04.685 --> 08:05.750
Nice.

08:05.752 --> 08:07.419
Joe:
<i> They said the next step</i>

08:07.421 --> 08:09.688
<i> Is putting together</i>
<i> some concrete data</i>

08:09.690 --> 08:12.290
<i> To show people that</i>
<i> the ideas are feasible.</i>

08:12.292 --> 08:13.958
<i> Who knows how they'll do that,</i>

08:13.960 --> 08:20.365
<i> But either way, I'm just glad</i>
<i> gene's keeping busy.</i>

08:20.367 --> 08:22.300
Announcer:
<i> Then he just steps across...</i>

08:22.302 --> 08:24.369
<i> [speaking indistinctly]</i>
<i> on his hands,</i>

08:24.371 --> 08:25.838
<i> But he's not quite</i>
<i> close enough.</i>

08:25.840 --> 08:27.239
Brought you some gifts.

08:27.241 --> 08:29.441
Perfect.
All we need is the hard drives.

08:29.443 --> 08:30.642
Got it.

08:30.644 --> 08:39.518
♪♪

08:39.520 --> 08:48.460
♪♪

08:48.462 --> 08:57.135
♪♪

08:57.137 --> 09:06.010
♪♪

09:06.012 --> 09:07.145
We could use that.

09:07.147 --> 09:09.481
I can't believe
I didn't think of that.

09:09.483 --> 09:12.551
♪♪

09:12.553 --> 09:16.088
Zero, one, one,

09:16.090 --> 09:19.758
One, zero, zero,

09:19.760 --> 09:24.028
One, zero, one, one...

09:24.030 --> 09:28.901
♪♪

09:28.903 --> 09:29.968
[ blows ]

09:29.970 --> 09:36.708
♪♪

09:36.710 --> 09:43.349
♪♪

09:44.451 --> 09:46.251
[ computer chiming ]

09:47.521 --> 09:53.057
Gabriel: Uh, gene.

09:53.059 --> 09:54.392
Gene:
Oh, my gosh!

09:54.394 --> 09:56.795
We figured out
how to predict the stock market!

09:56.797 --> 09:59.732
It tracks perfect
a full month out.

09:59.734 --> 10:05.204
Not what we set out to do...
But campaign funding, check!

10:06.741 --> 10:08.873
[ wind whistling ]

10:08.875 --> 10:09.708
Joe...

10:11.011 --> 10:14.446
Do you think the stock market
could be used for good?

10:17.684 --> 10:20.018
No.

10:20.020 --> 10:20.953
How come?

10:20.955 --> 10:22.388
Nothing.

10:23.757 --> 10:27.292
I've been thinking a lot
about your campaign lately.

10:27.294 --> 10:30.295
It'll be beautiful
if you can pull it off.

10:30.297 --> 10:33.632
Your ideas for
public transportation alone...

10:33.634 --> 10:37.702
We've cracked a big obstacle
that could give us some footing.

10:37.704 --> 10:40.372
But I've got
some real considering to do.

10:41.976 --> 10:43.642
I wish
I could help you more,

10:43.644 --> 10:47.112
But I kind of got my hands full
with my chair.

10:47.114 --> 10:48.513
It's good.

10:48.515 --> 10:51.383
We were
a little lost before.

10:51.385 --> 10:55.087
But now
we've both got our things.

10:56.323 --> 10:59.324
Well, what's next?

10:59.326 --> 11:03.328
I got a trial subscription
from imdb pro,

11:03.330 --> 11:04.729
And I got the address

11:04.731 --> 11:07.199
For andre benjamin's
manager's assistant from it.

11:07.201 --> 11:08.867
I'm going to write a letter
to him

11:08.869 --> 11:12.004
And see if he'd like
to be my vice president.

11:12.006 --> 11:13.806
Keep me updated.

11:13.808 --> 11:15.507
You too.

11:18.212 --> 11:19.478
[ ship horn blows ]

11:19.480 --> 11:22.581
Hey.
How's it going, guys?

11:31.692 --> 11:32.591
[ switch clicks ]

12:00.220 --> 12:08.426
♪♪

12:08.428 --> 12:16.634
♪♪

12:16.636 --> 12:18.370
[ door buzzes ]

12:18.372 --> 12:24.510
♪♪

12:24.512 --> 12:30.648
♪♪

12:30.650 --> 12:32.317
Hey.
Hey.

12:32.319 --> 12:33.719
What are you up to?

12:33.721 --> 12:35.653
Researching electricity.

12:35.655 --> 12:36.922
Nice.

12:36.924 --> 12:38.990
Gene's actually got a plan
to connect

12:38.992 --> 12:42.260
All the power grids
into one global supergrid.

12:42.262 --> 12:45.263
That would cost
$50 trillion.

12:45.265 --> 12:47.465
That's a lot.

12:47.467 --> 12:48.734
You want a drink?

12:48.736 --> 12:50.602
Mm, painkillers.
Oh.

12:50.604 --> 12:51.669
Well, okay.

12:51.671 --> 12:54.940
I'll make it
a small one.

12:54.942 --> 12:56.875
What are
you trying to do?

12:56.877 --> 13:00.346
I never spent that much
time down here before,

13:00.348 --> 13:02.214
And, uh...

13:02.216 --> 13:06.952
I don't think it's a long-term
solution if something happens.

13:06.954 --> 13:10.089
People weren't made
to live underground.

13:11.559 --> 13:13.625
Kind of like
that book you got me.

13:13.627 --> 13:14.960
You want to
move upstairs?

13:14.962 --> 13:17.563
Maybe further away.

13:17.565 --> 13:19.765
Did you drive by your
grandmother's house this week?

13:20.901 --> 13:22.033
Yeah.

13:22.035 --> 13:24.836
I thought you were gonna
stay away from that block.

13:24.838 --> 13:28.374
I know.
But they put a barn star on it.

13:28.376 --> 13:31.509
Sorry.

13:31.511 --> 13:32.778
How's the chair coming?

13:35.115 --> 13:36.448
Still got 10.

13:36.450 --> 13:37.715
[ chuckles ]

13:37.717 --> 13:40.185
I'm hoping
it will come together.

13:40.187 --> 13:41.253
It will.

13:41.255 --> 13:42.588
We'll see.

13:43.523 --> 13:44.990
There's a lot
of pressure.

13:44.992 --> 13:48.994
It feels like, as a guy who's
lost a certain amount of hair,

13:48.996 --> 13:51.663
I was expected
to get into woodworking.

13:51.665 --> 13:53.331
And that's not
what you did.

13:53.333 --> 13:55.000
No.

13:55.002 --> 13:58.070
Well, better that than being
expected to have a baby.

13:59.673 --> 14:01.139
Well...

14:01.141 --> 14:04.542
Look at us.
No kid deserves this.

14:04.544 --> 14:06.812
Sarah...
I didn't...

14:06.814 --> 14:08.647
Let's not go there now.

14:10.417 --> 14:12.084
All right.

14:12.086 --> 14:17.423
By the way, you have at least
a thousand yellow hairs left.

14:17.425 --> 14:19.625
[ chuckles ]

14:19.627 --> 14:21.092
Thanks.

14:21.094 --> 14:24.696
Uh, cheers.

14:24.698 --> 14:25.998
Cheers.

14:30.638 --> 14:32.538
Cheers.
Uh, cheers again.

14:49.389 --> 14:51.557
[ sanding continues ]

15:06.006 --> 15:07.139
Hi, john.

15:07.141 --> 15:09.341
I was thinking
about our conversation,

15:09.343 --> 15:11.677
And, uh, let's do it.

15:11.679 --> 15:17.215
Well, if it helps you out, joe,
it's a done deal.

15:17.217 --> 15:19.118
Sure.

15:32.766 --> 15:35.034
[ choir vocalizing ]

15:56.790 --> 15:58.524
[ knocking ]

15:58.526 --> 15:59.792
Hey.

16:00.928 --> 16:04.596
Wanted to give you this.
I know you like books, so...

16:04.598 --> 16:06.865
Wow.
Thanks, mike.

16:06.867 --> 16:08.934
Yeah, I just told the guy
at the bookstore

16:08.936 --> 16:10.135
What I think you're like,

16:10.137 --> 16:12.270
And he said
that you'd be into this, so...

16:12.272 --> 16:16.141
I've never heard of it,
but I'm excited to read.

16:16.143 --> 16:17.275
Yeah.

16:17.277 --> 16:19.077
Um, you know, I just wanted to
thank you

16:19.079 --> 16:21.679
For helping me
get that crow for kelsey.

16:21.681 --> 16:22.748
She really loves it.

16:22.750 --> 16:24.550
Of course.

16:24.552 --> 16:27.085
Well, I got my license back,

16:27.087 --> 16:31.757
So I'm gonna go take the family
for a drive.

16:31.759 --> 16:33.024
Nice.
Yeah.

16:33.026 --> 16:34.426
Good time of year
for that.

16:34.428 --> 16:35.627
Yeah.
It<i> is</i> nice.

16:35.629 --> 16:37.095
It's my favorite activity,

16:37.097 --> 16:39.631
I'm never gonna drink
and drive ever again.

16:39.633 --> 16:41.967
Okay.

16:41.969 --> 16:43.435
Okay.

16:43.437 --> 16:45.904
[ vocalizing continues ]

16:54.047 --> 16:56.181
[ vocalizing fades, ends ]

16:59.920 --> 17:01.286
[ birds chirping ]

17:08.262 --> 17:10.662
So, what are we doing here?
We're going for a drive?

17:10.664 --> 17:12.530
Yeah.
Is that okay?

17:12.532 --> 17:14.199
Sure.

17:14.201 --> 17:19.405
♪♪

17:19.407 --> 17:21.406
Thank you.

17:21.408 --> 17:29.681
♪♪

